shared_text:
Kansas Foundation for Agriculture in the Classroom
August 21 at 10:14 AM ¬∑

Could you use an extra $500 for your classroom?

CHS Foundation provides $500 grants each year to Pre-K-12th grade teachers who have classroom projects that use agricultural concepts to teach reading, writing, math, science, social studies, and more. Eligible projects include classroom and schoolyard gardens, embryology projects, aquaculture projects, and agricultural literacy reading programs, among others. Deadline for Applications is Sept. 15. The CHS Foundation and National Agriculture in the Classroom Organization partner each year to offer this grant opportunity. Applications can be submitted online. https://www.agclassroom.org/teacher/grants.cfm

Last night at the August 10 meeting, the Tonganoxie USD 464 Board of Education approved the Strategic Reopening Plan and Remote Learning Handbook. These documents, as well as many other documents, links, and resources will be on our website and will be updated as necessary. Please check our website often for the most up-to-date information.

We are also asking families to complete a form to let us know which Option for Learning you will be selecting for each of your children for the fall semester. Please refer to the documents and our website for more information regarding on-site learning, remote learning, and health & safety precautions that will help you make the best decision for each of your children. Please complete this form no later than Monday, August 17 at 10AM.

Thank you for your support and continued patience, as we are all in this together!

Public announcement:

The USD 464 Board of Education will be holding its regular monthly meeting tonight, August 10, 2020. The meeting begins at 6 P.M. at the Tonganoxie Elementary School Library. The district‚Äôs 2020-21 school reopening plans will be presented for approval.
This will be a public meeting, but all attendees must wear a mask and social distance. Patron comments will be allowed in accordance with board policy.
The meeting will not be live streamed due to technology limitations; however, the meeting will be recorded and uploaded to the district‚Äôs youtube on Tuesday, August 11, 2020. In addition, the Strategic Reopening Plan, Remote Learning Handbook, and three one-page summary documents will be distributed through various channels no later than Tuesday morning.
Your continued patience and understanding are appreciated as the staff, administration, and board work through these challenges.
Jim Bothwell, Board President

Tonganoxie High School
July 20 at 7:55 AM ¬∑

Before we get into the new school year we want to take some time to recognize a truly great man who dedicated many years to Tonganoxie High School. Brent Smith recently and quietly retired from THS. He served the students and staff at Tonganoxie High School for more than 20 years and left an indelible mark on all that he crossed paths with. We are proud of all he accomplished and we are all better people for having been able to work with him. Happy retirement Mr. Smith!! His wife Cherryl will also be retiring. We wish both of them the very best in their next chapter. Also, today is his birthday so help us in wishing him a happy birthday today! Congrats to Mr. and Mrs. Smith. We will miss you!!

Tonganoxie High School
July 11 at 2:19 PM ¬∑

Mrs. Crystal McCoy is excited to be joining us at THS and we are excited to have her! She had this to say: Hi there everybody!! My name is Crystal McCoy and I‚Äôm really excited about becoming an official Chieftain this upcoming school year. I‚Äôve lived in Tonganoxie with my husband and son for the past 5 years; my son is a 1st grader at TES. This school year will be my 6th year teaching, my precious 5 years were spent teaching Chemistry at Wyandotte High School in Kansas City, Kansas. I attended Park University and Pittsburgh State University for undergrad and graduate school.
In my free time I enjoy camping, reading, and doing anything outdoors with my family. I also spend a lot of time playing tennis at Chieftain Park. During the winter/spring I referee competitive club volleyball.
I became a teacher because I enjoy teaching children and watching them grow and mature into adults. I‚Äôm really looking forward to becoming more involved in our town, that has so much town and school spirit.

As individuals, communities, and a nation, we have been deeply affected by recent tragedies, including the death of George Floyd in Minneapolis, which are grim reminders of the social and racial injustice that continues to exist in our world.

Kansas schools have been enriched by the growing diversity of our state. As education leaders and citizens in our communities and state, we have a responsibility to increase our own social awareness and amplify previously underrepresented voices and perspectives.

Dr. King said, ‚ÄúThe ultimate tragedy is not the oppression and cruelty by the bad people but the silence over that by the good people.‚Äù

As education leaders, we must not be silent. Our students, especially our students living these injustices, need to hear our voices, more importantly we must listen to the voices that have not been heard. Let‚Äôs come together to listen, learn, and act to eliminate systemic racism.

There will be no in person registration for Driver's Education. Information about how to register, program dates, and safety measures can be found on our website as well. If you have a question about registering or other questions related to the Driver's Education program, please direct them to sphillips@tong464.org.

How do you thank teachers that suddenly find themselves teaching in a way they never imagined or were prepared for during a pandemic? We think our teachers deserve more then we could ever give them...we‚Äôre only the PTO...so we decided the best way to appreciate our teachers and support our local community this year was to let each teacher pick a local business they would like a $25 gift card from.

Teachers, thank you for all your hard work. You are amazing. We hope you enjoy your gift cards and have a fantastic summer. Y‚Äôall deserve it.

Here are the local business the TMS PTO was able to support. We would also like to give a special thanks to Brothers Market, Flashbacks and Mr. Tire for your donations...our goal was to support all of you by keeping our money local...but you insisted on helping us and we really appreciate it.

Congratulations to Tracey Waldeier (Tonganoxie, KS) for earning the Special Education-Gifted Outstanding Graduate Award!

Tracey serves as the Gifted Facilitator at Tonganoxie Middle School where she helps gifted students foster a growth mindset. She also works with general education teachers to differentiate their lessons to challenge, accelerate, and enrich gifted students. Tracey served as team captain for Tonganoxie Middle School who won Grand Prize in the 2019 Burns & McDonnell Battle of the Brains with a $50,000 grant for STEM education at Tonganoxie Middle School. Science City will construct an exhibit of their winning entry, ‚ÄúStep Right Up! The Science Behind Carnival Games.‚Äù Her future plans include serving as a program or curriculum director.

To watch the 2020 TTC Honors Ceremony, visit https://bit.ly/TTC2020Honors

Tonganoxie FFA Chapter
April 30 at 11:01 AM ¬∑

Senior Spotlight!

Our next senior spotlight goes out to Sydney Turner!

Sydney has been involved in FFA for the past three years. She has served as Junior Secretary and Chapter Reporter. Her favorite CDEs/LDEs are Vet Science and Public Speaking. Sydney's favorite FFA memory is National Convention and seeing Garth Brooks in concert. Her most proudest accomplishments are placing 1st in District Public Speaking and placing 7th as a team at State Vet Science.

Sydney is planning to pursue a career in History or Archaeology.

Advice to young FFA members: Get out of your box and try new things, I promise it's not as scary as you think!

Special Thanks: I want to thank my parents for encouraging me to go through with my dreams and helping me with everything whether it be listening to my speeches or going through flashcards.

Congrats Sydney! Thank you for your commitment and efforts to the Tonganoxie FFA Chapter!

Tonganoxie FFA Chapter
April 29 at 11:20 AM ¬∑

Senior Spotlight!

Our first senior spotlight is Ellie Braun!

Ellie has been an FFA member for the past four years. She has served as the Junior Sentinel, Chapter Secretary and Chapter Sentinel. Last year, she received her State FFA Degree. Ellie's favorite CDEs/LDEs are Land Eval, Discussion Meet and Agronomy.

Ellie plans to attend Kansas State University in the fall where she will study Agronomy.

Her advice to young FFA members: The more involved you are the more you get out of it! Never be afraid to try a new CDE or run for office!

Her special thanks: I want to thank both my parents, Mrs. Schartz and Mr.Maurer for all of their help and support and for pushing me to try and learn new things.

Congratulations Ellie! Thank you for all of your hard work and dedication to the Tonganoxie FFA Chapter!

We want all community members to be aware in the event someone is wondering why our stadium lights are on.

At 8:20 p.m. look toward the Beatty Field to see the glow of our support for our graduating class of 2020.

Feel free to drive by tonight with your family to recognize the Class of 2020.

Please stay in your vehicles and continue to follow CDC guidance of Social Distancing.

Let‚Äôs get the word out!

Stay safe and healthy.

Photo courtesy Jamie Lawson

‚Ä¢ The technology department will schedule a time for the students device to be dropped off for repair or replacement.

Internet Access

shared_text:
Tonganoxie Police Department is at Tonganoxie High School.
March 5 at 9:04 PM ¬∑ Tonganoxie, KS ¬∑

Today, the Tonganoxie Police and Tonganoxie City Fire Department partnered with Leavenworth County EMS, Kansas Department of Transportation and Tonganoxie High School students to create a mock car accident. The mock accident was to demonstrate the dangers of drunk driving. The student body was able to watch the Fire Department extract injured persons (student actors) from the crash, as well as police arrest the student drunk driver. The student role players did a phenomenal job in creating a realistic scene that impressed how to never drive impaired. KDOT also brought a speaker that spoke to the students during an assembly. Thanks to the students that participated and orchestrated this event!

Special thanks to Alvy Wise Salvage who donated the cars, and Heartland Tow Inc. Auto Repair & Service who moved them around for us!

#MirrorSports update: Tonganoxie High now has brought home two state titles in back-to-back seasons, thanks to Connor Searcy and Grayson Sonntag on Saturday. Searcy also won a title in 2019, while Sonntag placed third. Gabe Bailey nabbed a third-place finish this season as well, helping THS to a fourth=place team finish.

#MirrorSports update: Tonganoxie High will have a medalist at the inaugural KSHSAA girls wrestling championships. THS frosh Holly Colvert earned a pin vs. Burlington jr. Bryleigh Isch in the 191 consolation bracket midway through the second period (3:58). Colvert's next match will determine whether she advances to the consolation championship to wrestle for third place or is headed to the fifth-place match. Regardless, she will finish the day anywhere from third to sixth and bring home a medal.

Well this post is a little delayed, but I‚Äôm excited to say I have accepted the second Agriculture Teacher/FFA Advisor position at Tonganoxie High School! It will be strange walking the same halls I did in high school four years ago as a teacher now, but I‚Äôm eager to expand this Ag program and FFA chapter alongside Beth Schartz. THS will be the perfect place to start my teaching career as there is tremendous community support, allowing the opportunity for Tongie to have one of the best (if not THE best) Ag programs and FFA chapters in the state of Kansas!

Tonganoxie Elementary School
February 7 at 12:22 PM ¬∑

The Scholastic Book Fair is coming to TES!

There is a new secure digital option available for purchasing books for your child or school! It is called E Wallet and you can access that online at scholastic.com/fair.

There will be a Chiefs' Super Bowl Champions Poster available to pre-order at the Book Fair for $4.75! Posters will be delivered mid-March.

Book Fair Dates:

Wednesday, February 12th--Noon-8:00 p.m.

Thursday, February 13th--4:00-8:00 p.m.

Book Fair Location: Room 1132 in the 4th grade pod

If you are unable to attend the Fair in person, we invite you to visit our online Book Fair at scholastic.com/fair. Our Online Fair is available from February 6th-14th.

We look forward to seeing you and your family at our Book Fair! Remember, all purchases benefit our school.

Come support Chieftain Softball tomorrow night, Tuesday, February 4th, at our 3rd annual Chili & Soup Cookoff!

5:30-7:30 in the THS Chieftain Room during the THS Basketball Games

All you can eat soup, a dinner/cinnamon roll, and a drink for just $5!

Our players have been working hard on some delicious recipes and even the coaches are competing!

Hope to see you there!
